\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Dynamics of neuronal populations: eigenfunction theory; some solvable cases
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Population density approach models interacting populations instead of the
 individual dynamics of connected neurons 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Optical imaging of the cortex might be regarded as the motivation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Review
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Integrate-and-fire equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dv}{dt}=-\gamma v+s,\quad0\leq v\leq1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Membrane potential has been normalized such that 
\begin_inset Formula $v=0$
\end_inset

 marks the rest state and 
\begin_inset Formula $v=1$
\end_inset

 the threshold 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Given a threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{th}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{rest}}$
\end_inset

 we can make a variable transformation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v=\frac{V-V_{\text{res}t}}{V_{\text{th}}-V_{\text{rest}}}
\]

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
v(V_{\text{rest}}) & =0,\quad v(V_{\text{th}})=1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In general, the membrane potential could become negative, i.e.
 hyper polarized if the neuron receives strong enough inhibitory input 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Kistler and Knight have demonstrated with some rigour that the LIF equation
 can be derived from the Hodgkin-Huxley dynamics 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Under steady-state input agreement can be excellent 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Under variable input it remains a good approximation if the input modulation
 frequency is small relative to firing frequency 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Probability density 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial\rho}{\partial t}=-\frac{\partial}{\partial v}J=\frac{\partial}{\partial v}\left(\gamma v\rho-\frac{s}{h}\int_{v-h}^{v}\rho(v',t)dv'\right)=\frac{\partial}{\partial v}(\gamma v\rho)+\frac{s}{h}\rho(v-h)-\frac{s}{h}\rho(v)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compare to [Omurtag, A., Knight, B.
 W., & Sirovich, L.
 2002] 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\rho}{\partial t}=\gamma\frac{\partial(v\rho)}{\partial v}+\sigma(t)\left\{ \rho(v-h)-\rho(v)\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This needs to be solved given initial data 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(v,t=0)=\rho_{0}(v)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Integrate-and-fire dynamical model is nonlinear since the membrane potential
 is reset to zero upon reaching threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $v=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It forgets its past behavior 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The flux is composed of backward drift due to leakage 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma v$
\end_inset

 and a forward advection due to synaptic arrival rate
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma=s/h
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Boundary conditions 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Rate of the population 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)$
\end_inset

 is given by the flux of neurons leaving the threshold )
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r=J(v=1,\,t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Number of neurons is preserved, the flux of neurons leaving the interval
 must be equal to that entering at resting potential 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(\rho)_{v=0}=J(\rho)_{v=1}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If inhibitory input is present, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(\rho)+J(\rho)_{v=0^{-}}=J(\rho)_{v=0^{+}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Probability is conserved 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}\rho(v,t)dv=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Boundary condition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(v=1,t)=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Eigenfunction problem 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Eigenfunction equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma\frac{\partial}{\partial v}(v\phi)-\frac{s}{h}\left\{ \phi(v)-\phi(v-h)\right\} =\lambda\phi
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The partial time derivative on the l.h.s of the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\rho=\rho\frac{\partial}{\partial v}(\gamma v\rho)+\frac{s}{h}\rho(v-h)-\frac{s}{h}\rho(v)
\]

\end_inset

is replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(\phi)_{v=0}=J(\phi)_{v=1},\quad\phi(1)=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The flux condition ensures that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The flux is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
J & =-\gamma v\rho+\frac{s}{h}\int_{v-h}^{v}\rho(v',t)dv'=-\left(\gamma v\rho+\frac{s}{h}\rho(v-h)-\frac{s}{h}\rho(v)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Flux condition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(\phi)=-\left(\gamma v\phi+\frac{s}{h}\phi(v-h)-\frac{s}{h}\phi(v)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Flux 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(\phi)_{v=1}=-\frac{s}{h}\phi(1-h)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Flux 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(\phi)_{v=0}=-\gamma v\phi(0)+\frac{s}{h}\phi(0)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Eigentheory is governed largely by the dimensionless parameter 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\theta=\frac{s}{\gamma h}=\frac{\sigma}{\gamma}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Ratio of the synaptic arrival rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to the leakage rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In realistic situations 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is a large parameter 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For some purposes it is also convenient to regard 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 as a formal small parameter 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Flux condition 
\begin_inset Formula $J(0)=J(1)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{s}{h}\int_{0-h}^{0}\rho(v')dv'=\frac{s}{h}\int_{1-h}^{1}\rho(v,t)dv'
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We are at liberty to take 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=0$
\end_inset

 outside 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq v\leq1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This underlines the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 has delta function behavior at the origin 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
All neurons in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in(1-h,1)$
\end_inset

 which receive synaptic arrivals reappear at the origin 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Such neuron remain trapped at the origin until synaptic arrival jump the
 neurons to the membrane potential 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the arrival rate this delta function can be introduced explicitly 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\rho=\gamma\frac{\partial}{\partial v}(v\rho)-\sigma\left\{ \rho(v,t)-\rho(v-h,t)\right\} +\sigma A(t)\delta(v)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A(t)=\int_{1-h}^{1}\rho(v',t)dv'=A[\rho]$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Does this term enters naturally if one introduces the reset mechanism into
 the neuron dynamics? 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is constant we can make the variable transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\sigma t$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial}{\partial\tau}\rho=\frac{1}{\theta}\frac{\partial}{\partial v}(v\rho)+\rho(v-h)-\rho(v)+A[\rho]\delta(v)=L\rho
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Variable transformation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau=\sigma t
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Chain rule yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\rho_{t} & =\rho_{\tau}\frac{d\tau}{dt}=\rho_{\tau}\sigma
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma\rho_{\tau} & =\gamma\frac{\partial}{\partial v}(v\rho)+\sigma\left\{ \rho(v-h)-\rho(v)\right\} +\sigma A[\rho]\delta(v)\\
\rho_{\tau} & =\theta\frac{\partial}{\partial v}(v\rho)+\rho(v-h)-\rho(v)+A[\rho]\delta(v)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This form incorporate the flux boundary condition 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Starting from
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\rho=-\frac{\partial}{\partial v}J=-\frac{\partial}{\partial v}\left(J_{\text{str}}+J_{\text{imp}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

the flux is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
J_{\text{str}} & =-\gamma v\rho\\
J_{\text{imp}} & =\sigma\int_{v-h}^{v}\rho(v')dv'
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Additional term 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A[\rho]\delta(v)\rightarrow A[\rho]\Theta(v)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Eigenfunction equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L\phi=\lambda\phi,\quad\phi(1)=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Zero leak 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Equation 
\begin_inset Formula $18$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $21$
\end_inset

 are not transitionally invariant as a result of the leakage 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Forgetfulness engendered by the zero-reset condition also rules out translationa
l invariance 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Limit of zero-leak 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 with fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial}{\partial\tau}\rho=\rho(v-h)-\rho(v)+A[\rho]\delta(v)
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(t=0)=\rho_{0}(v)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the synaptic rate is a function of time, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=\sigma(t)$
\end_inset

, time dependence is transformed away by introducing 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau=\int_{0}^{t}\sigma(t)
\]

\end_inset

which reduces 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\rho}{\partial t}=\sigma\left\{ \rho(v-h)-\rho(v)+A[\rho]\delta(v)\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

to the above equation 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Variable transformation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau=\int_{0}^{t}\sigma(t')dt'
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Chain rule 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{t}=\rho_{\tau}\frac{d\tau}{dt}=\rho_{\tau}\sigma(t')
\]

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{\tau}=\rho(v-h)-\rho(v)+A[\rho]\delta(v)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Unnecessary assumption
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{h}=N
\]

\end_inset

is a integer 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compartmentalize the density so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(v,t)=\sum_{k=1}^{N}\rho_{k}(v,t)
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in[(k-1)h,\,kh]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Initial condition is similarly decomposed 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{0}(v)=\sum_{k=1}^{N}\rho_{k}^{(0)}(v)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}\rho_{n}=\rho_{n-1}-\rho_{n}+A[\rho_{N}]\delta(v)
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{n}(\tau=0)=\rho_{n}^{(0)}(v)
\]

\end_inset

which we assume to be smooth 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
After the first instant a delta function appears at the origin as a result
 of neurons getting exited in the last subinterval 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since the density evolves by incremental jumps of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, at the next instant a delta function appears at 
\begin_inset Formula $v=h$
\end_inset

, and at the following at 
\begin_inset Formula $2h$
\end_inset

, and so forth 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{k}(v,t)=\hat{\rho}_{k}(v,\tau)+D_{k}(\tau)\delta(v-(k-1)h)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The delta functions is located at the left border of the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[(k-1)h,\,kh]$
\end_inset

 on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{k}$
\end_inset

 is defined
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\rho}_{k}(v,\tau)$
\end_inset

 is smooth and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k}(0)$
\end_inset

 represents the strength of the delta function in the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th interval 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Initially 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k}(0)=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Decomposition in the first compartment 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}D_{1}=-D_{1}+A=-D_{1}+D_{N}+\int_{1-h}^{1}\hat{\rho}_{N}(v')dv'
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}\hat{\rho}_{1}=-\hat{\rho}_{1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Second interval 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}D_{2}=D_{1}-D_{2}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}\hat{\rho}_{2}=T_{h}\hat{\rho}_{1}-\hat{\rho}_{2}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{h}$
\end_inset

 is the translational operator 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{h}g(v)=g(v-h)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
These steps carry over to an arbitrary, and we define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\begin{pmatrix}-1 & 0 & \ldots &  &  & 0\\
T_{h} & -1 &  &  &  & \vdots\\
0 & T_{h} & -1\\
\vdots &  & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  &  & 0\\
0 & \ldots &  & 0 & T_{h} & -1
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Split 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=A-I
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\begin{pmatrix}0 & 0 & \ldots &  &  & 0\\
T_{h} & 0 &  &  &  & \vdots\\
0 & T_{h} & 0\\
\vdots &  & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  &  & 0\\
0 & \ldots &  & 0 & T_{h} & 0
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that for 
\begin_inset Formula $v=(0,1\ldots,)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Av=T_{h}v
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The smooth part 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\boldsymbol{\rho}}=[\hat{\rho}_{1},\ldots,\hat{\rho}_{N}]
\]

\end_inset

satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}\hat{\boldsymbol{\rho}}=L\hat{\boldsymbol{\rho}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The membrane potential is just a parameter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Translational operator commutes with time derivative
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The solution is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\boldsymbol{\rho}}=e^{\tau L}\boldsymbol{\rho}_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The matrix exponential 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e^{\tau L}=\begin{pmatrix}-1 & 0 & \ldots &  &  & 0\\
\tau T_{h} & -1 &  &  &  & \vdots\\
\frac{(\tau T_{h})^{2}}{2!} & \tau T_{h} & -1\\
\frac{(\tau T_{h})^{3}}{3!} & \frac{(\tau T_{h})^{2}}{2!} & \tau T_{h} & \ddots\\
\vdots &  &  &  &  & 0\\
\frac{(\tau T_{h})^{N-1}}{(N-1)!} & \frac{(\tau T_{h})^{N-2}}{(N-2)!} &  & 0 & \tau T_{h} & -1
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The matrix exponential is a shorthand for 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e^{\tau L}=\sum_{n}\frac{1}{n!}\left(\tau L\right)^{n}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Matrix 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
L^{2} & =\begin{pmatrix}-1 & 0 & \ldots &  &  & 0\\
T_{h} & -1 &  &  &  & \vdots\\
0 & T_{h} & -1\\
\vdots &  & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  &  & 0\\
0 & \ldots &  & 0 & T_{h} & -1
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}-1 & 0 & \ldots &  &  & 0\\
T_{h} & -1 &  &  &  & \vdots\\
0 & T_{h} & -1\\
\vdots &  & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  &  & 0\\
0 & \ldots &  & 0 & T_{h} & -1
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & \ldots &  &  & 0\\
-2T_{h} & -1 &  &  &  & \vdots\\
0 & T_{h} & -1\\
\vdots &  & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  &  & 0\\
0 & \ldots &  & 0 & T_{h} & -1
\end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We observe that the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 have the following structure 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We multiply the second column by 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset

 and add it the first column which yields 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
From this follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 has just one non-zero eigenvalue 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
One can check that 
\begin_inset Formula $v=(0,0,\ldots,1)$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=-1$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Check 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Lv=\begin{pmatrix}-1 & 0 & \ldots &  &  & 0\\
T_{h} & -1 &  &  &  & \vdots\\
0 & T_{h} & -1\\
\vdots &  & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  &  & 0\\
0 & \ldots &  & 0 & T_{h} & -1
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}0\\
0\\
\vdots\\
\\
0\\
1
\end{pmatrix}=-1\begin{pmatrix}0\\
0\\
\vdots\\
\\
0\\
1
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Other vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}=(0,\ldots0,1,0\ldots,0)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Start from
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\begin{pmatrix}-1 & 0 & \ldots &  &  & 0\\
T_{h} & -1 &  &  &  & \vdots\\
0 & T_{h} & -1\\
\vdots &  & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  &  & 0\\
0 & \ldots &  & 0 & T_{h} & -1
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gaussian Elimination: Multiply the first row with 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{h}$
\end_inset

 and add it to the second row 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sim\begin{pmatrix}-1 & 0 & \ldots &  &  & 0\\
0 & -1 &  &  &  & \vdots\\
0 & T_{h} & -1\\
\vdots &  & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  &  & 0\\
0 & \ldots &  & 0 & T_{h} & -1
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Multiply second row with 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{h}$
\end_inset

 and multiply add to the third row 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sim\begin{pmatrix}-1 & 0 & \ldots &  &  & 0\\
0 & -1 &  &  &  & \vdots\\
0 & 0 & -1\\
\vdots &  & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  &  & 0\\
0 & \ldots &  & 0 & T_{h} & -1
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This will give us 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}-1 & 0 & \ldots &  &  & 0\\
0 & -1 &  &  &  & \vdots\\
